<Article
  title="Why We Draw Our Own Maps Instead of Using Screenshots"
  description="Using in-game screenshots is faster and easier. We still choose to create clean, original SVG diagrams. Here’s why."
  kicker="Our Approach"
  date="2026-06-25"
  heading="Why We Draw Our Own Maps"
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="sec">
    <p>Most game guide sites just grab screenshots from the game. We spend the extra time drawing our own. It’s not about aesthetics — it’s about three practical problems with screenshots.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>Copyright and legal risk</h2>
    <p>Game artwork and UI belong to the developers. Using their screenshots on a site that runs ads (even indirectly) creates unnecessary exposure. We avoid that entirely by creating our own diagrams.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>Signal vs noise</h2>
    <p>A raw screenshot is full of irrelevant visual clutter: HUD elements, distant scenery, particle effects, and decorative objects. Players need clear information about task locations, kill zones, and safe paths.</p>
    <p>Our SVGs contain only what matters.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="sec">
    <h2>Long-term maintainability and mobile experience</h2>
    <p>When the game updates, a screenshot is often outdated immediately. SVGs are code — we can adjust a single point in seconds. They also scale perfectly on phones without becoming blurry.</p>
  </section>
</Article>
